Exercise 1¶

Use the pulse rates (beats per minute) of males. Begin with a lower class limit of 40 and use a class width of 10. Do the pulse rates of males appear to have a normal distribution?

In [11]:
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore', category=FutureWarning)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import numpy as np

# Filtering pulse rates for males
pulse_rates_males = df[df['GENDER (1=M)'] == 1]['PULSE']

# Define class intervals
class_width = 10
lower_class_limit = 40
upper_class_limit = pulse_rates_males.max() + class_width - (pulse_rates_males.max() % class_width)

bins = list(range(lower_class_limit, upper_class_limit + class_width, class_width))

# Histogram
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.histplot(pulse_rates_males, bins=bins, kde=True, color='blue', edgecolor='black')
plt.title('Histogram of Male Pulse Rates')
plt.xlabel('Pulse Rate (beats per minute)')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

The pulse rates in males do not seem to have a normal distribution. For more precise analysis, statistical tests are necessary.

Use the high-density lipoprotein (HDL) cholesterol measurements (mg>dL) from the 300 subjects included in Data Set 1 “Body Data”. Identify the highest value. Does it appear to be an outlier? Do the mean and median change much when that highest value is deleted?

In [50]:
hdl_measurements = df['HDL'].tolist()

# Highest value
max_value = max(hdl_measurements)

# Is the max value an outlier?
Q1 = df['HDL'].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df['HDL'].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1
upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

is_outlier = max_value > upper_bound

# Calculate mean and median
mean_before = df['HDL'].mean()
median_before = df['HDL'].median()

# Calculate mean and median without the highest value
hdl_measurements_without_max = [x for x in hdl_measurements if x != max_value]
mean_after = pd.Series(hdl_measurements_without_max).mean()
median_after = pd.Series(hdl_measurements_without_max).median()

# Print results
print(f"Highest value of HDL cholesterol: {max_value}")
print(f"Is the highest value an outlier? {is_outlier}")
print(f"Mean before removing the highest value: {mean_before}")
print(f"Median before removing the highest value: {median_before}")
print(f"Mean after removing the highest value: {mean_after}")
print(f"Median after removing the highest value: {median_after}")

Exercise 9¶

Based on Data Set 1 “Body Data”, males have red blood cell counts with a mean of 4.719 and a standard deviation of 0.490, while females have red blood cell counts with a mean of 4.349 and a standard deviation of 0.402. Who has the higher count relative to the sample from which it came: a male with a count of 5.58 or a female with a count of 5.23? Explain.ain.

In [56]:
# Given data
mean_male = 4.719
std_dev_male = 0.490
red_blood_cell_count_male = 5.58

mean_female = 4.349
std_dev_female = 0.402
red_blood_cell_count_female = 5.23

# Calculate z-scores
z_score_male = (red_blood_cell_count_male - mean_male) / std_dev_male
z_score_female = (red_blood_cell_count_female - mean_female) / std_dev_female

# Compare z-scores
if abs(z_score_male) > abs(z_score_female):
    print("The male with a count of 5.58 has a higher count relative to their sample.")
elif abs(z_score_female) > abs(z_score_male):
    print("The female with a count of 5.23 has a higher count relative to their sample.")
else:
    print("Both have counts that are equally distant from their respective sample means.")
    
print(f"Z-score for male: {z_score_male:.2f}")
print(f"Z-score for female: {z_score_female:.2f}")

The female with a count of 5.23 has a higher count relative to their sample.
Z-score for male: 1.76
Z-score for female: 2.19

Exercise 10¶

Diastolic Blood Pressure of Males Refer to Data Set 1 in Appendix B and use the diastolic blood pressures of males.

  1. Find the mean and standard deviation, and verify that the data have a distribution that is roughly normal. Round the results using three decimal places.
  2. Treating the unrounded values of the mean and standard deviation as parameters, and assuming that male diastolic blood pressures are normally distributed, find diastolic blood pressures separating the lowest 2.5% and the highest 2.5%. These values could be helpful when physicians try to determine whether diastolic blood pressures are significantly low or significantly high.
In [103]:
from IPython.display import display, Markdown

diastolic_bp_males = df[df['GENDER (1=M)'] == 1]['DIASTOLIC']

display(Markdown("**Part (a): Calculate mean and standard deviation**"))
mean_bp = diastolic_bp_males.mean()
std_bp = diastolic_bp_males.std()

mean_bp_rounded = round(mean_bp, 3)
std_bp_rounded = round(std_bp, 3)

# Results
print(f"Mean (rounded to three decimal places): {mean_bp_rounded}")
print(f"Standard Deviation (rounded to three decimal places): {std_bp_rounded}")

# Plots
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
sns.histplot(diastolic_bp_males, kde=True)
plt.title('Histogram of Diastolic Blood Pressure of Males')
plt.xlabel('Diastolic Blood Pressure')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
stats.probplot(diastolic_bp_males, dist="norm", plot=plt)
plt.title('Q-Q Plot')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

display(Markdown("**Part (b): Calculate the 2.5th and 97.5th percentiles**"))
z_025 = stats.norm.ppf(0.025)
z_975 = stats.norm.ppf(0.975)

# Convert z-scores to diastolic blood pressures
bp_025 = mean_bp + z_025 * std_bp
bp_975 = mean_bp + z_975 * std_bp

# Results
print(f"Diastolic blood pressure separating the lowest 2.5%: {bp_025:.3f}")
print(f"Diastolic blood pressure separating the highest 2.5%: {bp_975:.3f}")

Assume that women have diastolic blood pressure measures that are normally distributed with a mean of 70.2 mm Hg and a standard deviation of 11.2 mm H.:

  1. Find the probability that a randomly selected woman has a

normal diastolic blood pressure level, which is below 80 mm Hg.2. e Find the probability that a randomly selected woman has a diastolic blood pressure level between 60 mm Hg and 80 mm H3. ure Find P90, the 90th percentile for the diastolic blood pres ure levels of wo4. ssure If 16 women are randomly selected, find the probabilit that the mean of their diastolic blood pressure levels is less than 75 mm Hg.

In [70]:
import scipy.stats as stats

# Given data
mean_bp = 70.2
std_bp = 11.2

# Exercise 1
prob_below_80 = stats.norm.cdf(80, mean_bp, std_bp)
print(f"1. Probability that a randomly selected woman has a diastolic blood pressure level below 80 mm Hg: {prob_below_80:.4f}")

# Exercise 2
prob_between_60_and_80 = stats.norm.cdf(80, mean_bp, std_bp) - stats.norm.cdf(60, mean_bp, std_bp)
print(f"2. Probability that a randomly selected woman has a diastolic blood pressure level between 60 mm Hg and 80 mm Hg: {prob_between_60_and_80:.4f}")

# Exercise 3
p90 = stats.norm.ppf(0.90, mean_bp, std_bp)
print(f"3. The 90th percentile for the diastolic blood pressure levels of women (P90): {p90:.4f}")

# Exercise 4
sample_size = 16
std_error = std_bp / (sample_size ** 0.5)
prob_mean_less_than_75 = stats.norm.cdf(75, mean_bp, std_error)
print(f"4. Probability that the mean diastolic blood pressure of 16 women is less than 75 mm Hg: {prob_mean_less_than_75:.4f}")

1. Probability that a randomly selected woman has a diastolic blood pressure level below 80 mm Hg: 0.8092
2. Probability that a randomly selected woman has a diastolic blood pressure level between 60 mm Hg and 80 mm Hg: 0.6280
3. The 90th percentile for the diastolic blood pressure levels of women (P90): 84.5534
4. Probability that the mean diastolic blood pressure of 16 women is less than 75 mm Hg: 0.9568

Exercise 14¶

Refer to Data Set 1 “Body Data” and construct a 95% confidence interval estimate of the mean pulse rate of adult females; then do the same for adult males. Compare the results.

In [71]:
pulse_females = df[df['GENDER (1=M)'] == 0]['PULSE']
pulse_males = df[df['GENDER (1=M)'] == 1]['PULSE']

# Calculate 95% confidence interval
def confidence_interval(data, confidence=0.95):
    n = len(data)
    mean = data.mean()
    std_err = stats.sem(data) 
    h = std_err * stats.t.ppf((1 + confidence) / 2, n - 1)
    return mean, mean - h, mean + h

# Confidence intervals
mean_females, ci_lower_females, ci_upper_females = confidence_interval(pulse_females)
mean_males, ci_lower_males, ci_upper_males = confidence_interval(pulse_males)

# Results
print(f"Female Pulse Rate: mean = {mean_females:.2f}, 95% CI = ({ci_lower_females:.2f}, {ci_upper_females:.2f})")
print(f"Male Pulse Rate: mean = {mean_males:.2f}, 95% CI = ({ci_lower_males:.2f}, {ci_upper_males:.2f})")

# Compare results
if ci_lower_females > ci_upper_males:
    comparison = "The confidence intervals do not overlap. Female pulse rates are significantly higher than male pulse rates."
elif ci_upper_females < ci_lower_males:
    comparison = "The confidence intervals do not overlap. Male pulse rates are significantly higher than female pulse rates."
else:
    comparison = "The confidence intervals overlap. There is no significant difference between female and male pulse rates."

print(comparison)

Female Pulse Rate: mean = 74.04, 95% CI = (72.00, 76.09)
Male Pulse Rate: mean = 69.58, 95% CI = (67.77, 71.39)
The confidence intervals do not overlap. Female pulse rates are significantly higher than male pulse rates.

Exercise 15¶

Data Set 1 “Body Data” includes weights of 153 randomly selected adult males, and those weights have a standard deviation of 17.65 kg. Because it is reasonable to assume that weights of male medical students have less variation than weights of the population of adult males, we can be conservative by letting s = 17.65 kg. How many male medical students must be weighed in order to estimate the mean weight of all male medical students? Assume that we want 90% confidence that the sample mean is within 1.5 kg of the population mean. Does it seem reasonable to assume that weights of male medical students have less variation than weights of the population of adult males?

In [72]:
import scipy.stats as stats

# Given values
sigma = 17.65
E = 1.5
confidence_level = 0.90

# (Z_alpha/2) for 90% confidence level
alpha = 1 - confidence_level
z_alpha_over_2 = stats.norm.ppf(1 - alpha / 2)

# Required sample size
n = (z_alpha_over_2 * sigma / E) ** 2
n = int(np.ceil(n))

print(f"Required sample size: {n}")

Required sample size: 375

import pandas as pd
import statsmodels.api as sm

data = df[['GENDER (1=M)', 'HEIGHT', 'WEIGHT']].dropna()

# Add a constant to the predictor variables (intercept)
X = sm.add_constant(data[['height', 'weight']])

# Fit logistic regression model
model = sm.Logit(y, X).fit()

# Print the summary of the model

probability = model.predict(new_data)[0]
print(f"Probability that the subject is male given a height of 170 cm and weight of 90 kg: {probability:.4f}")

from scipy.stats import pearsonr

hdl = df['HDL']
ldl = df['LDL']

# Calculate correlation coefficient
correlation, p_value = pearsonr(hdl, ldl)
print(f"Correlation coefficient: {correlation:.4f}, P-value: {p_value:.4f}")

# Perform linear regression
X = sm.add_constant(hdl) 
model = sm.OLS(ldl, X).fit()
print(model.summary())

# Regression line equation
intercept, slope = model.params
print(f"Regression line equation: LDL = {intercept:.4f} + {slope:.4f} * HDL")

# Plot the data and the regression line
sns.scatterplot(x=hdl, y=ldl)
plt.plot(hdl, intercept + slope * hdl, color='red')
plt.xlabel('HDL')
plt.ylabel('LDL')
plt.title('HDL vs. LDL')
plt.show()

# Separate data by gender
for gender in [0, 1]:
    gender_df = df[df['GENDER (1=M)'] == gender]
    hdl_gender = gender_df['HDL']
    ldl_gender = gender_df['LDL']

    # Calculate correlation coefficient
    correlation_gender, p_value_gender = pearsonr(hdl_gender, ldl_gender)
    print(f"\nGender: {'Female' if gender == 0 else 'Male'}")
    print(f"Correlation coefficient: {correlation_gender:.4f}, P-value: {p_value_gender:.4f}")

    # Perform linear regression
    X_gender = sm.add_constant(hdl_gender)  # Add a constant term to the predictor
    model_gender = sm.OLS(ldl_gender, X_gender).fit()
    print(model_gender.summary())

    # Regression line equation
    intercept_gender, slope_gender = model_gender.params
    print(f"Regression line equation: LDL = {intercept_gender:.4f} + {slope_gender:.4f} * HDL")

    # Plot the data and the regression line
    sns.scatterplot(x=hdl_gender, y=ldl_gender)
    plt.plot(hdl_gender, intercept_gender + slope_gender * hdl_gender, color='red')
    plt.xlabel('HDL')
    plt.ylabel('LDL')
    plt.title(f'HDL vs. LDL ({ "Female" if gender == 0 else "Male"})')
    plt.show()

Exercise 21¶

Given the pulse rates in Data Set 1 “Body Data”, use two-way analysis of variance to test for an interaction effect, an effect from the row factor of age bracket, and an effect from the column factor of gender. Use a 0.05 significance level.

In [105]:
from statsmodels.formula.api import ols
import statsmodels.stats.anova as anova

data = df[['AGE', 'GENDER (1=M)', 'PULSE']].dropna()
data.columns = ['age', 'gender', 'pulse']

# Age brackets
bins = [0, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 100]
labels = ['0-20', '21-30', '31-40', '41-50', '51-60', '60+']
data['age_bracket'] = pd.cut(data['age'], bins=bins, labels=labels, right=False)

# Create the model formula
formula = 'pulse ~ C(age_bracket) + C(gender) + C(age_bracket):C(gender)'

# Fit the model
model = ols(formula, data=data).fit()

# ANOVA
anova_table = anova.anova_lm(model, typ=2)

# ANOVA table
print(anova_table)

# Interaction plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
ax=sns.pointplot(x='age_bracket', y='pulse', hue='gender', data=data, markers=["o", "s"], linestyles=["-", "--"],
              palette={0: 'coral', 1: 'blue'})
plt.title('Interaction Plot of Pulse Rate by Age Bracket and Gender')
plt.xlabel('Age Bracket')
plt.ylabel('Mean Pulse Rate')
handles, labels = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()
labels = ['Female', 'Male']
plt.legend(handles, labels, title='Gender')
plt.show()

# Main effect plots
# Age Effect
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.boxplot(x='age_bracket', y='pulse', data=data)
plt.title('Main Effect of Age Bracket on Pulse Rate')
plt.xlabel('Age Bracket')
plt.ylabel('Pulse Rate')
plt.show()

# Gender Effect
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.boxplot(x='gender', y='pulse', data=data)
plt.title('Main Effect of Gender on Pulse Rate')
plt.xlabel('Gender')
plt.ylabel('Pulse Rate')
plt.xticks([0, 1], ['Female', 'Male'])
plt.show()
